        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: accept valid MCP tool schemas without strict inputSchema.type check",
        "body": "## Summary\nFixes MCP server loading failure when tools have `inputSchema` without explicit `type: \"object\"`.\n\nCloses #63602\n\n## Changes\n- `listAllTools` validates each `tools/list` page **once** with `RelaxedListToolsResultSchema` and catalogs **that same validated payload** — there is no strict-then-relist flow, so a stateful or hostile server cannot pass validation with one response and have a different response consumed (no validation-to-use gap).\n- `RelaxedToolSchema` is **derived from the pinned SDK's own `ToolSchema`** (`ToolSchema.extend` / `ToolSchema.shape.inputSchema.extend`) and differs from it at exactly one point: the root `inputSchema.type` is an optional string instead of `z.literal(\"object\")`. Every other field — `outputSchema`, task `execution` metadata, `annotations`, pagination — keeps the exact pinned SDK contract, so malformed metadata still rejects the page.\n- After every page parse, the SDK's `cacheToolMetadata()` is invoked with the validated tools — the same side effect `client.listTools()` runs — so `callTool()` enforces output-schema validation and task-required guards identically to the SDK flow. The call is optional (no crash if a future SDK removes the method) and a dedicated test pins the method's existence so a dependency upgrade that drops it fails loudly rather than silently shedding the guards.\n- `normalizeInputSchema()` backfills `type: \"object\"` only when the field is missing; `isValidRootInputSchema()` + the catalog gate skip tools with an explicit non-object root type (e.g. `\"string\"`, `\"array\"`) with a `logWarn`. Server `toolCount` reports accepted tools only.\n\n## Root Cause\nThe MCP SDK v1.29.0 `ToolSchema` validates `inputSchema.type` as `z.literal(\"object\")`. Some MCP servers (especially older SDKs or custom implementations) omit `type` from `inputSchema`, returning `{ properties: { ... } }`, which trips a Zod validation error: `invalid_value expected \"object\" in inputSchema.type` and crashes the whole catalog.\n\n## v6 notes (current revision)\nAddresses the P1 from the latest review (validation-to-use gap, confidence 0.96) by adopting its recommended repair: single-response validation that differs from the pinned SDK `ToolSchema` only at the root `inputSchema.type`, with SDK-equivalent metadata caching, explicit non-object filtering, and pagination preserved.\n- The strict-then-relist flow is gone entirely; the request count per page is 1 in all cases.\n- New stateful-server regression: a server that returns a benign typeless payload on request 1 and a malicious payload on request 2 gets exactly one `tools/list` request, and only the validated payload is cataloged. **Mutation-checked**: against the previous strict-then-relist implementation this test fails with the catalog containing the drifted (never-strictly-validated) tool — reproducing the reported attack — and the server log showing two list requests.\n- New SDK-seam pin test: `Client.prototype.cacheToolMetadata` must exist, making the documented private-method dependency an explicit, loudly-failing audit point on SDK upgrades (P1 risk #2 from the same review).\n- Relaxation-scope unit tests: malformed `outputSchema`, malformed `execution.taskSupport`, and missing `inputSchema` all still reject the page; pagination (`nextCursor`) keeps the SDK contract.\n\n## Real behavior proof\nBehavior or issue addressed: Bundle MCP tool cataloging accepts tools whose root `inputSchema` omits `type` by validating each `tools/list` response once against a schema derived from the pinned SDK contract (relaxed only at the root `inputSchema.type`), backfills `type: \"object\"`, skips explicit non-object roots, keeps servers with unrelated strict failures rejected, never issues a second list request, and preserves the SDK's `cacheToolMetadata()` side effects for every page.\n\nReal environment tested: Local OpenClaw checkout on macOS from the rebased PR head, Node 25.2.1, pnpm 11.2.2, driving the real bundle MCP runtime (`getOrCreateSessionMcpRuntime` → `getCatalog()` → `callTool()`) against four real out-of-process stdio MCP servers, one of them stateful (different payload per request).\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: Ran `pnpm test src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-runtime.test.ts`, `pnpm tsgo:core`, `pnpm tsgo:core:test`, `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-runtime.ts src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-runtime.test.ts`, and `pnpm exec oxfmt --check --threads=1` on both files, plus a live four-server e2e script via `pnpm exec tsx`.\n\nEvidence after fix:\n```text\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\n     Tests  42 passed (42)\npnpm tsgo:core / tsgo:core:test: clean\noxlint / oxfmt --check: clean\n\ne2e (four live stdio servers):\ntools: [\"legacySdkServer/search_docs\",\"driftServer/benign_typeless_tool\"]\nservers: {\"legacySdkServer\":{\"toolCount\":1},\"driftServer\":{\"toolCount\":1}}\nrejected: [\"badOutputServer\",\"mixedServer\"]\ndriftServer tools/list requests received: 1        // exactly one — no second-request window\ncallTool(search_docs) → McpError -32600: Tool search_docs has an output schema but did not\n  return structured content                        // metadata cache populated from the same response\n```\n\nObserved result after fix: A `tools/list` payload whose `inputSchema` omits `type` catalogs cleanly with `type: \"object\"` backfilled; an explicit `type: \"array\"` sibling is skipped with a logWarn; servers with malformed `outputSchema` (alone or mixed with a repairable tool) stay rejected; a stateful server attempting response drift receives exactly one list request and only its validated payload is cataloged; `callTool()` enforces `outputSchema` for typeless tools exactly as the SDK strict flow would.\n\nWhat was not tested: A live third-party MCP server connected to an actual model-provider tool call was not tested in this environment.\n",
